title: For Sale:  Swedish LAHTI M40 - 9mm Semi-Auto, Excellent with Extras
postcontent:
I've had this pistol in my private collection for almost 25 years and have enjoyed owning it. 
 However everything must go at some point, and now is the time for this spectacular & collectible pistol. 

Pistol is in at least 95% overall condition. It's a single action semi-auto and resembles the German Luger, however it's much more robustly built. It's chambered in standard 9mm Luger. 

Metal finish is excellent with very few handling marks. Grips are perfect & bore is bright/shiny with no rusting, pitting, or other imperfections whatsoever. 

Pistol was made in 1944 by Husqvarna (Sweden) and It is 100% original - not an arsenal refurb or refinished piece. It is one of about 10,000 that was contracted by and then sold to Denmark. It is stamped with the Danish military/police unit marks, plus all of the normal Swedish proof and inspection marks. All numbers on pistol match, however Lahti magazines are not numbered. 

There is a very similar pistol listed right now (by Jackson Armory) on Gunbroker for $1595. 

Pistol comes with a correct & original holster/belt that is black leather with brass hardware in very good condition. Also included are 4 original magazines, oiler, cleaning rod, magazine loader/screwdriver tool, & original Lahti leather lanyard. Plus 3.5 boxes of collectible 9mm ammo by Sako. The ammo is beautiful for 1950's production and has SINOXOID non-corrosive primers. 

My asking price for everything is $1300 or best reasonable offer.  

FTF transaction with pickup in Brandon Florida. You must be at least 21 and a Florida resident to purchase. A proper bill of sale will be provided. 

I'd be happy to arrange a time for a serious buyer to inspect this pistol in person as the photos don't do it justice. 

Thanks for looking

I'm selling/trading my Chiappa Rhino 50DS in .357 magnum. Still has original box, manual, and brush. It's only had about 200 rounds put through it and still runs like it did when it was new. Has a rail under the barrel so you can attach your favorite flashlight or laser.

If you don't know about the Rhinos, they have their barrels aligned with the lowest cylinder, so the recoil from each shot goes straight back into your wrist and reduces muzzle rise. A rhino will have much less felt recoil and muzzle rise than a conventional magnum revolver. .38 specials out of the Rhino feel like .22lr's and you can go through a box of .357 mag without having sore wrists afterwards. Designed by the same man who designed the Mateba Autorevolver, the Rhino shares a lot of the same characteristics, mainly the lower axis barrel. 

I'm in no big hurry to sell this pistol, I just don't have the time to shoot it anymore and would prefer to have a semiautomatic pistol for home defense. 

I'd prefer to trade this for a HK 45, HK USP (or compact), or a double stack 1911, Sig Sauer 1911, a glock 34 with some cash, ammo, or accessories on your end, but will also take $850 cash for it. Contact me via email with offers, worse I can say is no and will respond to all offers.
